          "id": "sh-l05-c1",
          "title": "CHAPTER 6",
          "content": "Chapter 6: Science Red in Tooth and Claw. In the year 1787, something remarkable happened in New Jersey. A curious person stumbled upon a gigantic thighbone that was sticking out of the bank of a stream at a place called Woodbury Creek. This wasn't just any bone; it belonged to a creature that had long vanished from the Earth, likely a hadrosaur, which is known as a large duck-billed dinosaur. At that time, the concept of dinosaurs was completely unknown to scientists and the general public! The discovery of this bone was incredibly important because it opened the door to understanding these fascinating creatures that roamed the planet millions of years ago. The bone was carefully sent to Dr. Caspar Wistar, who was one of the most respected anatomists in the United States at that time. He took great care in studying the bone and later presented his findings at a meeting of the American Philosophical Society in Philadelphia that autumn. This presentation was a significant moment in the history of science, as it marked the beginning of our journey into the world of dinosaurs. Although many people at that time did not fully grasp the importance of this discovery, it laid the groundwork for future paleontological studies and sparked curiosity about the ancient life that once existed on Earth. The story of this thighbone reminds us of how much there is to learn about our planet's past and the incredible creatures that once inhabited it.\nContext recap: Chapter 6: Science Red in Tooth and Claw. In the year 1787, something remarkable happened in New Jersey. A curious person stumbled upon a gigantic thighbone that was sticking out of the bank of a stream at a place called Woodbury Creek. This wasn't just any bone; it belonged to a creature that had long vanished from the Earth, likely a hadrosaur, which is known as a large duck-billed dinosaur.\nWhy this matters: CHAPTER 6 helps learners in Science connect ideas from A Short History of Nearly Everything to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
